Here's a clean summary of both approaches, plus the proof on why Microsoft OBO can't work natively with Confluence.

---

## Approach 1 — Atlassian Only (3LO)

**How it works:**
User consents once → your backend stores the refresh token → all future Confluence API calls are silent and backend-only.

**Flow:**
```
User → Atlassian consent screen (one time)
     → Your backend stores refresh_token
     → Backend silently refreshes → calls Confluence API as user
```

**Pros:**
- Simple, straightforward — one system to manage
- Native Confluence user-level access
- Well-documented by Atlassian

**Cons:**
- No enterprise identity layer (no Azure AD, no SSO)
- User must visit Atlassian's consent screen specifically
- Tokens tied to Atlassian account, not your corporate identity

**Best for:** Standalone integrations, simple apps, non-enterprise environments.

---

## Approach 2 — Microsoft OBO + Atlassian 3LO (Combined)

**How it works:**
User logs in via corporate Azure AD SSO → your backend uses Microsoft OBO to identify the user → uses stored Atlassian refresh token to call Confluence on their behalf.

**Flow:**
```
User → Azure AD login (corporate SSO)
     → Backend: Microsoft OBO token exchange (identity verification)
     → Backend: lookup stored Atlassian refresh_token by user email
     → Backend: refresh → call Confluence API as user
```

**Pros:**
- Leverages existing corporate SSO — no separate Atlassian login
- Microsoft OBO gives you a stronger, enterprise-grade identity chain
- Better audit trail — actions linked to corporate identity
- Users already logged into Microsoft don't notice any extra auth

**Cons:**
- More complex — two auth systems to manage
- Still requires one-time Atlassian consent per user
- More tokens to store and rotate

**Best for:** Enterprise environments where users are already on Microsoft 365 / Azure AD.

---

## Why Microsoft OBO Cannot Natively Replace Atlassian Auth

This is the critical point. Here's the proof from Atlassian's own official documentation:

**1. Confluence Cloud only accepts tokens from Atlassian's own auth server**

The Confluence Cloud REST API explicitly states: authentication is implemented via JWT or OAuth 2.0 only — and for direct REST API calls, it supports Basic Auth only. There is no mention of accepting third-party tokens. [Atlassian](https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/rest/v1/intro/)

**2. Atlassian's token endpoint is `auth.atlassian.com` — not Azure**

The Confluence API access token is obtained exclusively by posting to Atlassian's own token URL (`https://auth.atlassian.com/oauth/token`) and can only be used to access the Atlassian site on the user's behalf after going through Atlassian's own authorization flow. [Atlassian](https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/oauth-2-3lo-apps/)

**3. Azure AD + Confluence = SSO only (SAML), not API auth**

The Microsoft Entra SSO plugin for Confluence provides only SAML 2.0-based single sign-on — it does not extend to API-level authentication or token delegation. It is purely for login, not for programmatic API access. [Microsoft Learn](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/active-directory/saas-apps/ms-confluence-jira-plugin-adminguide)

**4. Confluence API's own auth methods are fixed**

The Confluence Cloud REST API authentication supports only two methods: OAuth 2.0 three-legged (user context via Atlassian) and API token via HTTP Basic Auth. There is no support for external token providers like Azure AD. [Stitchflow](https://www.stitchflow.com/user-management/atlassian-confluence/api)

---

## Side-by-Side Comparison

| | Atlassian 3LO Only | Microsoft OBO + Atlassian 3LO |
|---|---|---|
| User action required | Once (Atlassian consent) | Once (Azure login + Atlassian consent) |
| Identity provider | Atlassian | Microsoft Entra ID (primary) |
| Confluence API auth | Atlassian OAuth token | Atlassian OAuth token |
| Enterprise SSO fit | ❌ | ✅ |
| Complexity | Low | Medium-High |
| Can Microsoft OBO call Confluence directly? | — | ❌ Not possible |
| Best for | Simple integrations | Enterprise / Microsoft 365 orgs |

**Bottom line:** Microsoft OBO is a powerful identity layer but Confluence's API is a closed system — it only accepts tokens issued by `auth.atlassian.com`. Microsoft OBO must sit alongside Atlassian 3LO, not replace it.
